Saint Elisabeth.title: Birth / Memory
Saint Elisabeth.about: A stream of consciousness that flows through the mind and down into the gut. The horse came to me in a dream, blocking my path. An enemy? Thoughts seemed to spiral into confusion. Which way? My life ran through my mind and I became absorbed with the idea of myself. The Light seemed far, far away. Ideas seemed frightening. Ideas of birth, memory. I awoke feeling confused. I knew I had to confront the horse, but how? I turned to sound. I let the ideas run their course in sound. Here, I share with you a struggle to keep praying in the face of overthinking and fear. The horse has only the power I allow it. The Light is never beyond us.

Saint Elisabeth.title: Christ in the Desert
Saint Elisabeth.about:
I find myself in an incredible state of spiritual dryness. I am keenly aware of my emptiness, my hollowness. This can be a blessing, a suffering brought about for a period to prepare the soul for the future rains of Grace. At the moment, my mind feels displaced from my body, a horror. I know that I must accept this torment, but also build the strength to fight my way to the Light. I must climb out of my guts and into Love.
Here we see Christ depicted in Dryness, which will explode into Love. For the moment, He is still.. The Sound is that of brittle humanity, felt by me always, felt by Him for a moment.

Saint Elisabeth.title: Christus
Saint Elisabeth.about:
A new release from Saint Elisabeth, Christus has required many hours of simple sound and meditation. This album is a prayer, a plea for rest that can only be provided by Christ. I turn to the Lord in my brokenness. My physical and emotional sufferings are offered up for others in unity with Christ and His Passion. May we all use our discomfort to purge sin from our lives, strengthen our commitment to God, and come together as deeply compassionate human beings.
The two tracks here are straightforward walls of noise, as I wanted to strip everything unnecessary out of my mind, soul, and the project. These sounds feel right, and the release has been very helpful in maintaining my balance and focus. Love to you all.

Saint Elisabeth.title: Inferno
Saint Elisabeth.about:
Dante, master of the Catholic Imagination. I begin my study of the Divine Comedy. The poem is divided into three major sections, Inferno, Purgatorio, and Paradiso. Here, my sounds are concerned with Inferno. Muffled and rumbling, this is my soundtrack to Dante"s horrific darkness.
On a journey through the Underworld with Virgil, the poets reach the ninth and final circle of Hell,containing the frozen lake called Cocytus. Dante presents a vision of sinners encased in ice, in all sorts of strange and twisted positions. Here we find the ultimate sinners, those who were treacherous, malicious and deceitful. This is the dwelling place of Satan, who torments the world's greatest traitor, Judas Iscariot.
Dante brilliantly visualizes a realm of complete removal from God.His use of ice instead of flame is a stunning portrayal of the emptiness that we feel if we turn from God.We are left frozen and trapped without Light and Warmth. In future releases, I plan on delving into the other two acts of The Divine Comedy; Purgatorio and Paradiso. I will follow the journey of Dante from darkness and sin to the revelation of the divine light, culminating in the Beatific Vision of God.

Saint Elisabeth.title: Saint Francis in Ecstasy
Saint Elisabeth.about:
All of a sudden there was a dazzling light. It was as though the heavens were exploding and splashing forth all their glory in millions of waterfalls of colours and stars. And in the centre of that bright whirlpool was a core of blinding light that flashed down from the depths of the sky with terrifying speed until suddenly it stopped, motionless and sacred, above a pointed rock in front of Francis. It was a fiery figure with wings, nailed to a cross of fire. Two flaming wings rose straight upward, two others opened out horizontally, and two more covered the figure. And the wounds in the hands and feet and heart were blazing rays of blood. The sparkling features of the Being wore an expression of supernatural beauty and grief. It was the face of Jesus, and Jesus spoke. Then suddenly streams of fire and blood shot from His wounds and pierced the hands and feet of Francis with nails and his heart with the stab of a lance. As Francis uttered a mighty shout of joy and pain, the fiery image impressed itself into his body, as into a mirrored reflection of itself, with all its love, its beauty, and its grief. And it vanished within him. Another cry pierced the air. Then, with nails and wounds through his body, and with his soul and spirit aflame, Francis sank down, unconscious, in his blood.
The love of Christ into Francis. I ponder the miracle of Francis receiving the Stigmata. I am left with tremendous Hope and Mercy. I offer these sounds and textures as Thanks.
Painting : Francis of Assisi in Ecstasy (or The Ecstasy of Saint Francis) by the Italian Baroque master Michelangelo Merisi da Caravaggio

Saint Elisabeth.title: Silence
Saint Elisabeth.about:
This is a new sound for my Saint Elisabeth project. An atmospheric piece, Silence is directly inspired by the Ingmar Bergman film Persona. Audio from the film combines with ghostly, ambient sound to examine the lead character, Elisabet Vogler. Elisabet is an actress who freezes in silence during a stage performance. An attack of existential crisis, Elisabet continues to remain silent. She is hospitalized. What follows is a psychological probe into the very meaning of identity and personhood.
The voice you hear is a doctor at the hospital speaking to Elisabet, who is present, but silent. The doctor understands why this silence has been chosen. Isnâ€™t it better to stay quiet than to continue lying? To continue playing one of many characters? What is there left to say when all is false?
This resonates with me because I find myself desiring silence. I desire God. I need to listen. Iâ€™ve created so much noise, filling the air with words. Yet I realize I say little. I know nothing. I meet Elisabet Vogler at a place of desperation.
Best experienced on headphones, a little bit louder.
